sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_J36848
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Lac-inducible generator of Lpp-OmpA(46-66)-Streptavidin wild-type + His6tag
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
This device contains a lac promoter and strong ribosome binding site for lac-inducible expression of the fusion protein of Lpp signal peptide, OmpA aa46-66, and streptavidin wild-type + His6 tag. This expression should display streptavidin on the cell surface of E. coli.
NOTE ABOUT THE SEQUENCE: The mixed site between parts is 'only' six base pairs, ACTAGA. There is no spacer T or G nucleotide. These spacer nucleotides have been placed in the results for "get selected sequence" as an automatic composite-parts addition for the BioBricks mixed site between assembled parts. However, this does not apply between the R0010 and B0031 in the J04500 composite because that was assembled in a standard fashion.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Perry Tsai
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
There is no spacer nucleotide between the end of the device and the SpeI restriction site.
Also, the mixed site in between the parts is only six base pairs long, ACTAGA, without the spacer T or G in between parts. This does not apply between R0010 and B0031.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_J36836
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
This part codes for amino acids #46-66 of outer membrane protein A (OmpA). It corresponds to a single transmembrane domain of OmpA, crossing the outer membrane of E. coli.
This was fused with the lipoprotein signal peptide upstream and streptavidin downstream in the project to express streptavidin on the outer surface of E. coli.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Perry Tsai
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: There are no spacer nucleotides between the part and the XbaI restriction site, or between the part and the SpeI restriction site, so that the mixed site would be 6bp long, and reading frame would be maintained between protein domains.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_J36841
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Streptavidin, wild-type core + His6 tag (no start codon)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
This part codes for the core part of wild-type streptavidin protein, without the start codon. Streptavidin protein binds strongly to the biotin molecule, and can be used to bind biotinylated nucleic acids or peptides.
There is a histidine tag added at the end of the coding sequence right before the stop codons. You can probe for this protein with an anti-his(C-term) antibody.
It was used as part of a fusion protein with lipoprotein signal peptide and outer membrane protein A transmembrane domains, to express streptavidin on the outer surface of E. coli.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Perry Tsai
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: PCR off a plasmid obtained from Alice Ting's lab at MIT.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
There was originally a XbaI site TCTAGA at nucleotides 118-123 of the part, which was mutated to AGCCGC. It is missing its start codon at the beginning, as the intention was to fuse this with surface display domains upstream.
There are no spacer nucleotides between the part and the XbaI restriction site, or between the part and the SpeI restriction site, so that the mixed site would be 6bp long, and reading frame would be maintained between protein domains.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_J36835
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
This codes for the 20-amino-acid signal peptide and the 1st nine amino acids of lipoprotein. When fused with another protein downstream, the signal peptide should target the protein to the outer membrane of E. coli, facing the periplasm.
This part was fused with OmpA(aa46-66) and OmpA(aa46-159) in trying to express streptavidin protein on the outer surface of E. coli.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Perry Tsai
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: There is no spacer nucleotide between the part and the SpeI restriction site, so that after BioBricks assembly, the mixed site is 6 base pairs, and the reading frame is maintained between protein domains.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0034
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Vinay S Mahajan, Voichita D. Marinescu, Brian Chow, Alexander D Wissner-Gross and Peter Carr IAP, 2003.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Varies from -6 to +1 region from original sequence to accomodate BioBricks suffix.

No secondary structures are formed in the given RBS region. Users should check for secondary structures induced in the RBS by upstream and downstream elements in the +50 to -50 region, as such structures will greatly affect the strength of the RBS. Contact info for this part: Brian Chow

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: LacI
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
Inverting regulatory region controlled by LacI (BBa_C0010, BBa_C0011, etc.)

The pLac regulatory region is a 243 base-pair sequence with standard BioBrick prefix and suffix sections on its ends. It contains two protein binding sites: CAP, which is generally present in E.coli and is assocciated with cell health and availability of glucose., and LacI, the Lac inhibitor BBa_C0010 which binds in an dimerized cooperative manner to inhibit the transcription of the protein that follows. In the presence of lactose or IPTG, an analog of lactose, LacI is unable to correctly bind and inhibit transcription. This allows BBa_R0010 to be used as a inverter or as a detector of lactose or IPTG.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The Plac insert was PCR'd from the MG1655 strain of E.coli K12.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: LacI binds to this regulator. This part is incompatible with species containing active LacI coding regions. Lactose and IPTG disable the operation of LacI and this regulator. This part is incompatible with environments containing lactose or lactose analogs.
